<DocsLayout title="Android Platform" currentPath={`${base}/android/`}>
  <h1>Android Platform</h1>
  <p class="text-lg text-muted-foreground !mt-2">
    State management in the Android ecosystem: ViewModel + StateFlow, Compose, and emerging alternatives.
  </p>

  <hr />

  <h2 id="viewmodel-stateflow">ViewModel + StateFlow</h2>

  <p><strong>Paradigm:</strong> Push &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Status:</strong> Google's standard recommendation</p>

  <p>The <code>ViewModel</code> + <code>StateFlow</code> pattern is the <strong>de facto standard</strong> for Android state management. ViewModels survive configuration changes, and <code>StateFlow</code> provides observable state streams that integrate with both Compose and the View system.</p>

  <h3>ViewModel with Derived State</h3>
  <Code code={viewModelCode} lang="kotlin" />

  <h3>Compose Integration</h3>
  <Code code={viewModelViewCode} lang="kotlin" />

  <h3>Characteristics</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Manual wiring:</strong> Derived state requires explicit <code>combine()</code> calls listing all dependencies</li>
    <li><strong><code>stateIn()</code> configuration:</strong> Must specify scope, sharing strategy, and initial value</li>
    <li><strong>No dependency graph:</strong> Adding a new source to a derived value requires modifying the <code>combine()</code> call</li>
    <li><strong>Lifecycle-aware:</strong> <code>WhileSubscribed(5000)</code> stops upstream collection when no subscribers remain for 5 seconds</li>
  </ul>

  <p>This pattern works well for straightforward cases but becomes verbose when the derived state graph is complex &mdash; every dependency must be manually listed in <code>combine()</code>.</p>

  <hr />

  <h2 id="compose-derivedstateof">Compose <code>derivedStateOf</code></h2>

  <p><strong>Paradigm:</strong> Pull + Graph &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Scope:</strong> UI-layer only</p>

  <p>Jetpack Compose's <code>derivedStateOf</code> provides <strong>automatic dependency tracking</strong> within the Compose runtime. The Snapshot system records which <code>State&lt;T&gt;</code> values are read during evaluation and only re-evaluates when those specific values change.</p>

  <h3>Usage</h3>
  <Code code={derivedStateCode} lang="kotlin" />

  <h3>How the Snapshot System Works</h3>
  <Code code={derivedStateExplainCode} lang="kotlin" />

  <h3>Key Strength: Conditional Invalidation</h3>
  <p><code>derivedStateOf</code> performs a two-level check: first whether source states changed, then whether the derived result changed. This prevents cascading recomposition when source data changes but the derived value remains stable (e.g., a filter that produces the same list after a data refresh).</p>

  <h3>Key Limitation: UI-layer Only</h3>
  <p>The Snapshot system is <strong>part of the Compose runtime</strong>. It cannot be used in ViewModels, Repositories, or any non-Compose code. For business logic derived state, developers must fall back to <code>StateFlow.combine()</code> &mdash; losing the automatic tracking.</p>

  <p>This creates a <strong>split model</strong>: automatic graph-based tracking in the UI layer, manual wiring everywhere else.</p>

  <hr />

  <h2 id="reactivestate-kotlin">ReactiveState-Kotlin</h2>
  <p class="not-prose text-sm text-muted-foreground"><a href="https://github.com/ensody/ReactiveState-Kotlin" class="underline underline-offset-4 hover:text-foreground">github.com/ensody/ReactiveState-Kotlin</a></p>

  <p><strong>Paradigm:</strong> Pull + Graph &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Scope:</strong> Business logic (any layer)</p>

  <p>ReactiveState-Kotlin fills the gap that <code>derivedStateOf</code> leaves: <strong>graph-based derived state for business logic</strong>. It uses the familiar <code>get()</code> pattern (like Jotai) for automatic dependency tracking, and it works in any layer &mdash; ViewModel, Repository, shared KMP modules.</p>

