  <Code code={reactiveStateObserveCode} lang="kotlin" />

  <h3>Kotlin Multiplatform</h3>
  <Code code={reactiveStateKmpCode} lang="kotlin" />

  <h3>Characteristics</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Auto-tracking via <code>get()</code> inside <code>derived {"{}"}</code></li>
    <li>Works in any layer (not limited to UI)</li>
    <li>Kotlin Multiplatform compatible</li>
    <li>Transitive dependencies tracked automatically</li>
  </ul>

  <hr />

  <h2>Why Graph-based Hasn't Taken Off on Android</h2>

  <p>Despite the advantages of graph-based state management, the Android ecosystem has been slow to adopt it outside of Compose's UI layer. Several factors contribute:</p>

  <h3>1. Google's Ecosystem Dominance</h3>
  <p>Google provides an opinionated, well-documented stack: <code>ViewModel</code> + <code>StateFlow</code> + <code>Hilt</code> + <code>Room</code>. Most teams follow the official guidance, and Google's samples reinforce this pattern. Third-party state libraries face an uphill battle against the platform vendor's recommendations.</p>

  <h3>2. MVI/MVVM Entrenchment</h3>
  <p>The Android community has converged on MVI (Model-View-Intent) and MVVM patterns. These patterns work well with StateFlow and don't require dependency graphs. Libraries like Orbit MVI and MVIKotlin provide structured alternatives within the push-based paradigm.</p>

  <h3>3. Flow as the Foundation</h3>
  <p>Kotlin <code>Flow</code> is deeply integrated into the Android ecosystem: Room returns <code>Flow</code>, Retrofit integrates with <code>Flow</code>, DataStore uses <code>Flow</code>. The reactive foundation is push-based, making it natural to stay push-based for state management.</p>

  <h3>4. Compose's Partial Solution</h3>
  <p><code>derivedStateOf</code> solves the most visible pain point (UI-layer derived state) without requiring external libraries. For many teams, this is "good enough" &mdash; the remaining manual wiring in ViewModels is tolerable.</p>

